Final Report: Tic-Tac-Toe Game

This project is a terminal-based two-player Tic-Tac-Toe game written in Python. Two players take turns entering a row and column to place X or O on a 3x3 board. After each move, the program displays the updated board and checks whether a player has won or whether the game has ended in a draw. The program also validates input so players cannot enter values outside the board or choose a space that is already taken. The goal of the project was to create a simple but complete game while practicing important Python programming concepts.

The program is organized using functions so that each part of the game has one clear job. One function creates the board, one prints the board, one checks for a winner, one checks for a draw, and another handles player input. The main game loop keeps running until one player wins or the board is full. After each valid move, the program checks rows, columns, and diagonals for a win. If there is no winner and all spaces are filled, the game ends in a draw. Organizing the program in this way made the code easier to read and easier to manage.

The main data structure used in this project is a 2D list, or list of lists. The board is stored as three lists inside one main list. Each inner list represents one row, and each element represents one position on the board. This structure is useful because it matches the layout of the Tic-Tac-Toe board and makes it easy to access a position by using row and column indexes such as `board[row][col]`. It also makes checking rows, columns, and diagonals straightforward. Using this structure helped keep the program simple and efficient.

One challenge was input validation because users can enter letters, blank input, or numbers outside the allowed range of 0 to 2. Another challenge was correctly checking all winning combinations, including horizontal, vertical, and diagonal patterns. It was also important to prevent players from choosing a space that was already occupied. These problems were solved by using repeated input checks and separate functions for game logic. Testing different move combinations helped confirm that the game worked correctly.

This project helped me practice Python skills such as loops, conditionals, lists, functions, and user input. It also showed the importance of planning a program before writing it. Breaking the game into smaller parts made the code easier to understand, test, and improve. I also learned that even a simple game requires careful logic in order to handle all possible situations correctly.

Another important part of this project was making the game easy for users to follow. Since the program runs in the terminal, the instructions and board display needed to be clear. Players have to understand whose turn it is, where they can place their mark, and why a move is invalid if the program rejects it. Making the interaction simple and understandable improved the overall quality of the game. This project showed that a program is not only about correct logic, but also about creating a good experience for the user.

This project also showed me how important program organization is. If all of the code had been written in one long section, it would have been much harder to understand and fix mistakes. By separating the game into smaller functions, I could focus on one part at a time and make sure each part worked correctly before moving on. This made the development process smoother and helped me better understand how the pieces of the program connect to one another.

A possible improvement would be adding a single-player mode where a user can play against the computer. The program could also be improved by keeping score across multiple rounds, allowing players to enter their names, or creating a graphical version of the game. Another useful improvement would be adding automated tests to make sure the main game functions continue to work correctly. Overall, this project was a useful learning experience and a good example of how Python can be used to create an interactive program.

Overall, creating this Tic-Tac-Toe game was a useful experience because it combined problem-solving, logic, and user interaction in one project. Even though the game itself is simple, it required careful thinking to make sure every part worked correctly. Completing this project gave me more confidence in my Python skills and showed me how programming concepts learned in class can be applied to build a full working program.

